584
00:49:53.500 --> 00:50:02.000
During the past year, we saw a planet literally on fire from Australia to California to Siberia.

585
00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:15.000
Droughts that produce millions of climate refugees, unprecedented heavy precipitation events and floods with costs and human lives and infrastructure damage in the trillions of dollars.

586
00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:27.000
We know we must take action to avoid leaving behind an unlivable planet with an erratic climate that will no longer support human civilization.

587
00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:47.000
Conservative estimates by the world's climate scientists state that to achieve climate stabilization and avoid cataclysmic changes, emissions of CO2 and other greenhouse gases must be brought down to at least 80 to 95 percent below 1990 levels by 2050.

588
00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:53.500
This won't be easy and it won't be cheap, but we have options.

589
00:50:53.500 --> 00:51:00.500
And the best option, according to economists, is putting a price on carbon emissions.

590
00:51:00.500 --> 00:51:08.500
Currently, the environmental health and social costs of carbon emissions are not included in carbon prices.

591
00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:20.000
These are treated as externalized costs that are borne directly and indirectly by Americans in their impaired health and increased morbidity and mortality.

592
00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:26.500
There's no such thing as a free market when it comes to energy.

593
00:51:26.500 --> 00:51:32.000
It's rife with monopolies, regulatory regimes, asymmetric information, and asymmetric power.

594
00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:45.500
When it comes to fossil fuels, there are dozens of direct and indirect subsidies, which economists call externalities, buried in the tax code or in plain view.

595
00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:51.500
And they all come with costs, tens of billions of dollars annually.

596
00:51:51.500 --> 00:52:00.000
These externalities distort the economic calculus of producers and consumers, be they households, businesses, or government entities.

597
00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:07.000
In short, they distort the market, burden society, and the rest of the economy.

598
00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:10.500
Nobody pays the true price of carbon.

599
00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:16.000
Conservative estimates put direct subsidies annually at $20 billion a year.

600
00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:27.000
For economists, the value of a pricing system lies in its ability to capture all the costs associated with that particular good.

601
00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:36.500
Fossil fuel externalities, including social costs, environmental costs, and health costs, are not being borne by those imposing them.

602
00:52:36.500 --> 00:52:40.500
They're being borne by the rest of us.

603
00:52:40.500 --> 00:52:50.500
Addressing those externalities could save taxpayers billions of dollars in societal costs while improving health and the quality of life.

604
00:52:50.500 --> 00:52:59.500
National and regional carbon pricing systems are being developed as we speak, carbon fee and dividend in particular.

605
00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:08.000
It can protect low and middle income citizens from the economic impacts of rising prices and fees.

606
00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:22.000
It can deliver dividends directly to every person in the country if it's a national regime or regionally if that is the way that it is being imposed.

607
00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:36.000
Because low and moderate income earners spend less than they receive out of these dividend payments, actually imposing carbon fees spurs spending and leads to direct economic growth.

608
00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:43.000
And this has been demonstrated around the world in countries where it's been developed.

609
00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Carbon pricing spurs market-driven innovation and market efficiencies, which will reduce harmful pollution and leave a healthier, more stable, and more prosperous nation for future generations.

