2181
03:43:18.500 --> 03:43:25.000
I'm going to focus right now on the rural aspect of this problem.

2182
03:43:25.000 --> 03:43:30.000
Today, towns must go it alone for universal broadband acquisition.

2183
03:43:30.000 --> 03:43:45.000
The existing RSA 53G creates a path for individual towns and their municipal partners to create an entity that can contract for district-wide services, but only on a piecemeal basis.

2184
03:43:45.000 --> 03:44:03.500
Each town would have to create its own administrative units, possibly beginning with their existing planning committee, which would then create a body called the Communication District, as well as a governing board for the Communication District.

2185
03:44:03.500 --> 03:44:13.000
As the law stands now, this effort would have to be duplicated by every other municipality across the state.

2186
03:44:13.000 --> 03:44:24.500
The municipalities that most need better broadband, particularly poor and rural communities, will be the least well-equipped to navigate this administrative process successfully.

2187
03:44:24.500 --> 03:44:32.500
What's unique about House Bill 153 is that it addresses the administrative obstacles to universal broadband.

2188
03:44:32.500 --> 03:44:40.500
Universal broadband access for all New Hampshire households and businesses should be a state policy goal.

2189
03:44:40.500 --> 03:45:02.500
The proposed legislation would create a study committee to identify the most effective way to achieve wholesale universal broadband access across the state for every resident of every municipality in New Hampshire, while avoiding the duplicative and redundant administrative mechanism described in RSA 53G.

2190
03:45:02.500 --> 03:45:27.500
The newly enacted House Bill 1111 from last session introduced new language into Section 3 of RS 33 Part 3G that essentially says that if an ISP does not respond to a request for information about served locations, within two months the municipality may declare that area to be unserved.

